    transcript: `Domain-submitted idea: Exception research for payments clients takes a lot of analyst and manager time. We think AI could help summarize issues and create better status updates.

Bot: What workflow should we explore first?
Domain Lead: The weekly payment exception tracker and client status pack. It starts when the client sends a tracker or asks for an update, and it ends with a client-ready status pack and action list.
Bot: Give me the rough A-to-Z process.
Domain Lead: 1. Analyst pulls the tracker from SharePoint, email, or client portal. 2. They compare it against the prior tracker and look for new rows, stale items, missing owners, and status changes. 3. They research exceptions in the client portal, emails, meeting notes, and internal project notes. 4. They summarize the exceptions into themes. 5. They draft status deck bullets and an action table. 6. Manager reviews accuracy, tone, action owners, and what can be said to the client.
Bot: What data is handled?
Domain Lead: Transaction IDs, client names, amounts, reason codes, comments, status, aging, owner, and action needed. Sometimes there is customer PII, so we need to be careful.
Bot: What systems or access constraints matter?
Domain Lead: Not every engagement gives us portal access. If not, we ask the client for exports or screenshots. The exception tracker screenshot shows status, reason code, owner, aging, and action needed.
Bot: Time and capacity impact?
Domain Lead: Comparing trackers takes 45 minutes to two hours. Research takes two to four hours. Manager review takes 30 to 60 minutes plus back-and-forth. This happens weekly or twice weekly across 8 to 12 projects per year. If AI helped, analysts could spend less time cleaning and summarizing, and managers could review instead of rewrite.
Bot: What are Product or Engineering open questions?
Domain Lead: Whether the tool can work with files and screenshots only when we do not have system access, and what data we are allowed to put into it.`
